{% block content %}
<header>
  <span class="icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-apple-whole"></i></span>
  <h1>The Word of Wisdom</h1>
  <p>A divine health code revealed to Joseph Smith in 1833 — governing what Latter-day Saints eat, drink, and abstain from, and why it matters spiritually.</p>
</header>

<main>

  <div class="intro-banner">
    <strong>More than a diet.</strong> The Word of Wisdom (Doctrine &amp; Covenants 89) is one of the most distinctive marks of LDS identity. It is not merely a health recommendation — for active members it is a covenant standard tied to temple worthiness and understood as a sign of obedience, self-mastery, and care for the body as a divine gift.
  </div>

  <!-- Scripture -->
  <div class="scripture-block">
    "A Word of Wisdom, for the benefit of the council of high priests, assembled in Kirtland, and the church, and also the saints in Zion — To be sent greeting; not by commandment or constraint, but by revelation and the word of wisdom…"
    <cite>— Doctrine &amp; Covenants 89:1–2</cite>
  </div>

  <!-- History -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-scroll"></i> &nbsp;History &amp; Background</div>
  <div class="narrative">
    <p>On February 27, 1833, Joseph Smith received the revelation now known as Section 89 of the Doctrine &amp; Covenants at the School of the Prophets in Kirtland, Ohio. According to Joseph's account, Emma Smith and others had complained about the tobacco smoke and chewing tobacco left behind by the school's participants. Joseph inquired of the Lord and received what he recorded as a "word of wisdom."</p>
    <p>Notably, the revelation itself says it was given "not by commandment or constraint" — suggesting it was advisory rather than binding at first. For much of the 19th century, observance was inconsistent. <strong>Coffee and tea were not universally prohibited</strong> even among faithful members until the early 20th century.</p>
    <p>The shift came under President Heber J. Grant (1918–1945), who consistently enforced the Word of Wisdom as a requirement for full fellowship and temple attendance. Since then, strict observance has been a defining marker of active LDS life. Today, compliance is asked about in temple recommend interviews.</p>
    <p>Modern prophets have also applied it to illegal drugs and, more recently, vaping and marijuana use — even where legal — citing both the spirit of the law and the principle of not placing addictive substances in the body.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- What to Avoid -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-ban"></i> &nbsp;What Members Avoid</div>
  <div class="rule-grid">
    <div class="rule-card avoid">
      <span class="rc-tag">Prohibited</span>
      <span class="rc-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-wine-glass"></i></span>
      <h3>Alcohol</h3>
      <p>All alcoholic beverages are prohibited. The revelation specifies that wine and strong drinks are "not for the belly." Sacrament is administered with water, not wine.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="rule-card avoid">
      <span class="rc-tag">Prohibited</span>
      <span class="rc-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-smoking"></i></span>
      <h3>Tobacco</h3>
      <p>All tobacco products are prohibited for consumption. The revelation allows tobacco for "bruises and all sick cattle" but not for human consumption.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="rule-card avoid">
      <span class="rc-tag">Prohibited</span>
      <span class="rc-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-mug-hot"></i></span>
      <h3>Coffee &amp; Tea</h3>
      <p>"Hot drinks" in the revelation have been interpreted by church leaders to mean coffee and tea (specifically black, green, and oolong teas derived from the <em>Camellia sinensis</em> plant). Herbal teas are generally permitted.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="rule-card avoid">
      <span class="rc-tag">Prohibited</span>
      <span class="rc-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-syringe"></i></span>
      <h3>Illegal Drugs &amp; Harmful Substances</h3>
      <p>Modern guidance extends the principle to illegal drugs, recreational marijuana, vaping, and misuse of prescription medications — anything addictive or harmful to the body.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- What Is Encouraged -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-seedling"></i> &nbsp;What Is Encouraged</div>
  <div class="rule-grid">
    <div class="rule-card encouraged">
      <span class="rc-tag">Encouraged</span>
      <span class="rc-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-wheat-awn"></i></span>
      <h3>Grains as a Staple</h3>
      <p>The revelation calls grain — especially wheat — "the staff of life," and encourages it as a dietary foundation. Corn, oats, and barley are also mentioned.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="rule-card encouraged">
      <span class="rc-tag">Encouraged</span>
      <span class="rc-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-carrot"></i></span>
      <h3>Fruits &amp; Vegetables</h3>
      <p>"All wholesome herbs" and fruits "in their season" are commended — eaten with "prudence and thanksgiving."</p>
    </div>
    <div class="rule-card encouraged">
      <span class="rc-tag">Use Sparingly</span>
      <span class="rc-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-drumstick-bite"></i></span>
      <h3>Meat</h3>
      <p>Flesh of animals is permitted but should be used "sparingly," and only "in times of winter, or of cold, or famine." Many members debate how strictly to apply this guidance.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="rule-card encouraged">
      <span class="rc-tag">Encouraged</span>
      <span class="rc-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-bed"></i></span>
      <h3>Rest &amp; Moderation</h3>
      <p>The revelation concludes with a promise of health, wisdom, and running without weariness to those who walk in obedience — implying general moderation and care for the body.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- The Promise -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-star"></i> &nbsp;The Promised Blessings</div>
  <div class="scripture-block">
    "And all saints who remember to keep and do these sayings, walking in obedience to the commandments, shall receive health in their navel and marrow to their bones; and shall find wisdom and great treasures of knowledge, even hidden treasures; and shall run and not be weary, and shall walk and not faint."
    <cite>— Doctrine &amp; Covenants 89:18–20</cite>
  </div>
  <div class="narrative">
    <p>The promised blessings are both physical (health and strength) and spiritual (wisdom, hidden treasures of knowledge, angelic protection). Many members report that the discipline required by the Word of Wisdom strengthens their overall self-mastery and spiritual sensitivity. The body is understood as a <strong>temple of the spirit</strong> — to be kept clean and undefiled.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Comparison with other traditions -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-scale-balanced"></i> &nbsp;Comparison with Other Christian Traditions</div>
  <div class="comparison-grid">
    <div class="comp-card">
      <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-cross"></i> Roman Catholic</h3>
      <span class="comp-sub">No general prohibition</span>
      <p>Catholicism has no blanket prohibition on alcohol, coffee, or meat. Fasting and abstinence (e.g., no meat on Fridays in Lent) are practiced, but these are periodic disciplines, not a permanent health code. Religious orders may have stricter rules.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="comp-card">
      <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-bible"></i> Protestant</h3>
      <span class="comp-sub">Varies by denomination</span>
      <p>Mainstream Protestant denominations (Lutheran, Anglican, Presbyterian, Methodist) generally permit alcohol in moderation. Some conservative Evangelical and Baptist groups practice total abstinence from alcohol but place no restrictions on coffee or tea.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="comp-card">
      <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-church"></i> Eastern Orthodox</h3>
      <span class="comp-sub">Fasting emphasis</span>
      <p>Orthodox Christianity has one of the most rigorous fasting traditions — abstaining from meat, dairy, fish, oil, and wine on Wednesdays, Fridays, and multiple multi-week fasts totaling over 180 days per year. But this is periodic discipline, not a permanent health code like the Word of Wisdom.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="comp-card">
      <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-people-group"></i> Adventist (closest parallel)</h3>
      <span class="comp-sub">Most similar to LDS</span>
      <p>Seventh-day Adventists observe a health code most similar to the Word of Wisdom — many are vegetarian, most avoid alcohol and tobacco, and some avoid caffeine. Like LDS, Adventists ground their health practices in theology: the body as God's temple.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Common Questions -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-circle-question"></i> &nbsp;Common Questions</div>
  <div class="faq-list">
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-mug-saucer"></i> Is caffeine prohibited?</h3>
      <p>Officially, <strong>no</strong>. The church clarified in 2012 that the only prohibited drinks are coffee and tea (and alcohol). Caffeinated sodas are not prohibited. The prohibition on coffee and tea is understood to relate to those specific drinks — not caffeine as a chemical — though individual members vary in their personal practice.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-leaf"></i> What about herbal tea?</h3>
      <p>Herbal teas (chamomile, peppermint, ginger, etc.) are generally considered acceptable because they are not derived from the <em>Camellia sinensis</em> plant. The restriction is on "tea" in the historical sense of black and green tea, not on every hot herbal beverage.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-wine-bottle"></i> Can members cook with alcohol or take communion wine?</h3>
      <p>LDS members do not take communion with wine — sacrament is administered with water. Using wine or spirits in cooking is a matter of personal conscience, though most faithful members avoid it. The church's sacrament prayers explicitly bless "water" as a substitute.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-building-columns"></i> Is the Word of Wisdom required for temple admission?</h3>
      <p><strong>Yes.</strong> Temple recommend interviews include a direct question about adherence to the Word of Wisdom. Members who consume alcohol, tobacco, coffee, or tea cannot hold a valid temple recommend, which is required for temple ordinances and serving in many leadership callings.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-flask"></i> What does modern science say?</h3>
      <p>Research on the health benefits of avoiding alcohol and tobacco has broadly validated what the revelation prescribed in 1833 — well before modern epidemiology. Studies on Latter-day Saints (particularly at UCLA) have found significantly lower rates of cancer and heart disease compared to the general population. The coffee and tea question is more nuanced, as moderate consumption of each is associated with some health benefits in non-LDS research.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

</main>

<footer>
  <p>LDS &amp; Christianity · Theological comparisons for education and understanding</p>
</footer>
